{"title":"Statler: State-Maintaining Language Models for Embodied Reasoning","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"LLM-based robot planners (e.g., Code-as-Policies) condition only on action/observation histories and struggle with long-horizon temporal reasoning and latent/unobservable dynamics, leading to brittle behavior on multi-step tasks.","method":"Statler introduces explicit world-state maintenance with two prompted LLMs. A world-state reader takes the user query plus the current JSON-formatted state and generates executable code for the robot; when state changes are implicated, the code calls update_wm to invoke a world-state writer. The writer updates the state estimate based on the action/query, and the updated state is stored in external memory and conditions future decisions. This model-based extension of CaP simplifies tracking and consulting state at each step and yields large gains on tabletop manipulation tasks and a real UR5 setup, especially on temporal queries (e.g., 83% vs. 31% on Pick-and-Place temporal queries; higher episode success across domains)."},{"problem":"Maintaining state via in-context demonstrations can demand substantial prompt engineering and be sensitive to example design; reducing this burden without losing robustness is challenging.","method":"Statler-Auto replaces the writer’s in-context examples with a concise natural-language instruction describing how to keep a commented JSON state, while retaining Statler’s reader/writer split and update_wm triggering. This instruction-only writer learns to update state without curated demos. Ablations show Statler-Auto achieves comparable individual-step success and often higher episode success in Pick-and-Place and Disinfection than default Statler and a unified reader/writer variant, reducing developer effort without sacrificing performance."}]}
